Related to #44539

We don't currently warn on trivially incorrect `NotNullIfNotNull` methods like the following:

```cs
[return: NotNullIfNotNull(nameof(param))]
string? Method(string? param) => null;
```

It feels like if you annotate that the behavior depends on the value of some input here, and you *never read that input*, something is wrong.

If we started to warn when such parameters are unread, we would catch the above case, and via the existing enforcement would continue to do the right thing in cases like the following:

```cs
[return: NotNullIfNotNull(nameof(param))]
string? Method1(string? param)
{
    if (param == null) { return null; } // ok
    // ...
}

[return: NotNullIfNotNull(nameof(param))]
string? Method2(string? param)
{
    if (param != null) { return null; } // warning CS8825: Return value must be non-null because parameter 'param' is non-null.
    return null; // ok
}

[return: NotNullIfNotNull(nameof(param))]
string? Method3(string? param)
{
    if (param == null) { return null; }
    return GetNullableString(); // warning CS8825: Return value must be non-null because parameter 'param' is non-null. 
}
```

We would continue to *not* warn in the following scenario, which will expose unexpected nulls to the caller. To handle these, we would have to make the investment of distinguishing *possibly null* from *definitely null*, which would be expensive. However, by catching the trivial scenario above I think we've added enough utility here to make the change worth making.
```cs
[return: NotNullIfNotNull(nameof(param))]
string? Method(string? param)
{
    OtherMethod(param);
    return null; // no warning
}

void OtherMethod(string? param2) { }
```

In the case of multiple `NotNullIfNotNull` attributes, I think we would only warn if *none* of the referenced inputs are read. Since use of multiple essentially has *or* semantics currently.

```cs
[return: NotNullIfNotNull(nameof(param1)), NotNullIfNotNull(nameof(param2))]
string? Method(string? param1, string? param2) => null; // warning: no inputs referenced by NotNullIfNotNull are read.

void Use()
{
    Method("a", null).ToString(); // ok
    Method(null, "b").ToString(); // ok
    Method(null, null).ToString(); // warning
}
```

cc @stephentoub who found that some methods were incorrectly annotated in runtime due to this gap.
